  "prompt": "For NSF Fellowship applicants, what is the difference between \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\"?",
  "response": "When evaluating NSF Fellowship applications, reviewers typically use a scale that includes ratings such as \"Excellent,\" \"Very Good,\" \"Good,\" and so on. The distinction between \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\" is nuanced and can vary depending on the specific criteria and standards of the review panel. However, here is a general outline of the difference:\n\n1. **Excellent:**\n   - **Intellectual Merit:** The application demonstrates outstanding potential for conducting original research. The applicant has a strong academic record, with compelling research experiences and clear, impactful research objectives.\n   - **Broader Impacts:** The proposal outlines significant contributions to society or advancements in the field. The applicant has a well-developed plan for engaging in activities that promote education, outreach, diversity, and inclusivity.\n   - **Clarity and Organization:** The application is exceptionally well-written, with a clear and coherent presentation of ideas and objectives. It effectively communicates the significance and feasibility of the proposed research.\n   - **Overall Impression:** The application stands out among peers, showcasing a high level of potential and preparation for graduate research.\n\n2. **Very Good:**\n   - **Intellectual Merit:** The application shows strong potential for research, with a good academic record and relevant research experiences, though it may lack some depth or originality compared to \"Excellent\" applications.\n   - **Broader Impacts:** The broader impacts are present and relevant, but they may be less innovative or not as thoroughly developed as those in \"Excellent\" applications.\n   - **Clarity and Organization:** The proposal is well-structured, but may have minor weaknesses in the presentation of ideas or research objectives.\n   - **Overall Impression:** The application is competitive, demonstrating promise for graduate research, but it might not be as distinguished in comparison to those rated as \"Excellent.\"\n\nIn summary, an \"Excellent\" rating indicates a top-tier application that exceeds expectations in key evaluation categories, while a \"Very Good\" rating reflects a strong, competitive application that may have some areas for improvement.",
